@* A number is information; a progress bar is feedback.
   A "book" in Hand and Foot needs 7 cards to complete. That used to be shown
   as a count ("5 / 7") and a gold glow when finished. Newcomers didn't read it.
   Adding a 7-pip row — one filled pip per card — made the goal legible at a
   glance: you can SEE how close a book is to closing without doing arithmetic.
   Cost: a for-loop and ~30 lines of CSS.

   Two other UI lessons live in this same component, almost for free:
     - Books are rendered sorted by rank (OrderBy below), so the strip reads
       like a sorted hand instead of reshuffling every time a new book starts.
     - The pip row carries an aria-label, so the visual feedback is also
       announced to assistive tech.

   Trimmed from UpAllNight.App.Shared.TeamBooks.razor. *@

<div class="books-grid">
    @foreach (var book in Books.OrderBy(b => RankOrder.GetValueOrDefault(b.Rank, int.MaxValue)))
    {
        <div class="book-card @(book.IsComplete ? "complete" : "")">
            <div class="book-rank">@book.Rank</div>
            <div class="book-info">
                <span class="book-count">@book.CardCount / @BookSize</span>
                <span class="book-type">@book.BookType</span>
            </div>

            @* The feedback that did the work: one pip per card, filled to count. *@
            <div class="book-progress" aria-label="@book.CardCount of @BookSize cards">
                @for (var i = 0; i < BookSize; i++)
                {
                    <span class="book-pip @(i < book.CardCount ? "filled" : "")"></span>
                }
            </div>
        </div>
    }
</div>

@code {
    [Parameter] public List<BookView> Books { get; set; } = new();

    private const int BookSize = 7;

    // Rank order is the reading order. Sorting the strip by it stops the layout
    // from reshuffling every time a new book is started.
    private static readonly Dictionary<string, int> RankOrder = new()
    {
        { "Four", 4 }, { "Five", 5 }, { "Six", 6 }, { "Seven", 7 }, { "Eight", 8 },
        { "Nine", 9 }, { "Ten", 10 }, { "Jack", 11 }, { "Queen", 12 }, { "King", 13 }, { "Ace", 14 }
    };
}
